# WAICT \- Web Application Integrity, Consistency and Transparency (External)

**Status of the document:** **Work in Progress**
**Authors:**
Benjamin Beurdouche (Mozilla)
Richard Hansen (Meta)
Ezzudin Alkotob (Meta)

**Last update:** February 18, 2025

**Overview**
Users of security sensitive Web Applications are currently quite vulnerable to attacks as they can be targeted with malicious web applications which would act differently with them than they would with other users. This document contains our detailed roadmap to build standard integrity and transparency mechanisms for Web Applications and a minimal cross-company alignment before starting standardization efforts.

**Current state**
We have a general agreement that these problems need solving and have a rough first cut solution for both the integrity and the transparency mechanisms. It turns out that implementing both together seems to be a more limited effort than implementing both individually as more problems occur when you don’t build both together. **We want to solve these problems for large websites and ensure the proposed solutions work for small websites at the lowest possible cost and complexity. This system is opt-in only and doesn’t require changes from the existing ecosystem if they don’t need the higher security level.**
Ideally we want to move both efforts to standardization soon, at W3C WebAppSec for the integrity part and possibly to the IETF for the transparency part.

### Introduction and Problem statement

#### Integrity requirements

**Users visiting sites need to be sure that the content they are getting has not been tampered with by any actor between the content creator and the delivery of the content.**

In the current ecosystem, websites do not have guarantees about the fact that users get delivered the authentic content they expected. They typically delegate the ownership of their TLS certificate to third parties such as CDNs which are trusted to deliver the content. This causes users to not know exactly which party is in control of the actual content they get served.

There are a few different kinds of possible issues in this area which range from misconfigurations on the content creator site or the serving party, to malicious insiders inside the organisations or even coercion of individuals or organizations by external parties. These issues can affect all users, a subset of them, or in some cases target users specifically.
These issues can be difficult to detect because they would require a monitoring party (that should ideally be the content creator) on all possible positions of the network where different content can be served (every geolocation, all possible times…).

Security critical websites want to solve those issues in order to avoid facing these threats whether the solution is process based or based on technical mitigations. As such they want to improve resilience against malicious employees performing undetected changes to the website or to be able to ensure employees are not coerced into performing actions on behalf of the site that would cause harm to the users.

Some cases of misconfigurations can also be difficult to detect. Integrity checks can help automatize the detection problems in a different way than traditional QA. Misconfiguration of websites might not break the site while changing the expected content of the page or serve deprecated versions of the content.

Overall, a few cases exist: websites that do not serve their own content do not necessarily want to trust third party hosting service with the integrity of their content; Users want to ensure they get access to the content that has not been modified by a third party; Websites that want to protect against malicious insider attacks; Websites that want to take additional steps to detect and protect against misconfigurations.

**To solve these issues, we propose to define and deploy an integrity and authenticity mechanism for critical resources in web pages by extending existing security mechanisms for the Web such as the Content Security Policy and the Sub Resource Integrity specifications and to add a manifest listing the resources in the page.**

#### Consistency requirements

**The users want to ensure that they are not targeted by the site and receive the same page as every other user with the exception of their private data.**

As Service Providers of security sensitive applications are often contributing to the overall security and privacy of the Internet, they are often considered as high value the target of infrastructure or legal requests that they need to comply with.

Users want to be able to check that they are not actively targeted and receive the same code as every other user. This does not mean that they can efficiently determine if the code served is malicious.

There are existing mechanisms that leverage Oblivious HTTP to ensure that multiple requests from multiple network paths do get the same content, however this check requires specific mechanics that can’t be provided easily by the browser or the site. These types of weak/local consistency mechanisms are sometimes useful but don’t provide the strong guarantee that *all* *users* get the same content.

**Increasing the value of the consistency properties**

Even in the presence of the consistency guarantees, it might be the case that every user gets attacked by the provider during a very short window of time where no user or auditor will catch the attack. Transparency helps with this problem by ensuring that this short attack window cannot be used to affect users. Having a proof of inclusion in a binary transparency log might be one of the solutions to explore there.

**We believe that we can achieve these guarantees in the case where the integrity and transparency mechanisms are deployed together. This property is one of the strongest that can be achieved and we want to encourage the ecosystem to reach it.**

#### Transparency requirements

**Dissuade websites from modifying sensitive values silently (eg. secure messaging)**

An important issue in the current infrastructures is authentication. In the context of secure messaging on the web, authentication guarantees are often provided by the application as it matches user names with identities whether it is done server side or locally. Similar to a native application, a website could lie to the user about how the encryption key is selected based on the identifier selected by the user. Even if the user has checked the identity key of another user is the correct one out of band via some QR code or something, the application can still encrypt to both the user and the adversary.

**Dissuade websites to exfiltrate sensitive values silently (eg. secure messaging)**

Service providers that perform computations on sensitive data inside the webpage typically have access to secrets (eg. Proton Mail or WhatsApp perform cryptographic computations in Js and WASM that are not supported by the WebCrypto API). Without the transparency property, there is nothing that prevents adversarial websites from exfiltrating the keys. Even if a Web API is used to protect key material the plaintext typically needs to be sent back into the page which remains under the control of the potentially adversarial website. In this context the transparency is a deterrent as a casual audit of the page could reveal misbehavior from the site.

**Providing visibility and long term auditability of the code to External auditors**

Real time visibility on the code allows users and third parties to ensure that the code that is distributed to them is accessible by more than one user at a time. This reinforces the consistency properties for the users.

Providing an append-only log of the code to third parties for a reasonable period of time ranging from a few months to a few years, in fact makes it potentially feasible for auditors to build an eternal record of the resources they are interested in.

**Protects against “after the fact modifications”**

One of the attacks that need to be mitigated is the modification of the resources being displayed after the fact. The scenario is the following: a content delivery service serves content at a version N to a client and replaces that version by another version N’ with the same version number in the repository that contains all served applications. This would break the expected consistency and transparency guarantees expected and can be prevented by the transparency log while it cannot be by simply signing the manifest.

**Protecting the users from being served malicious or buggy code by mistake**

Sites often want to be able to protect their applications against shipping incorrect or malicious code by mistake or sabotage, and having a set of protections prevents companies from both legal and reputational repercussions that can be caused by such unexpected circumstances. In case external circumstances cause companies to be coerced lawfully or otherwise, 	transparency mechanisms ensure visibility on what is being served to the users.

### Ecosystem impact and requirements

**Sites that do not advertise the integrity, consistency and transparency features and browser that don’t support the feature will work as currently expected**

There is no impact of enabling the mechanism in the browser if the website doesn’t support and advertise the mechanism. Similarly, if the mechanism is enabled by the website and the browser does not support it, the browser will just ignore it to make sites work on legacy browsers.

**Avoiding to change the way people package or serve their sites as much as possible**

Large websites typically do not inline or refer to scripts by ES modules. Instead they typically package javascript modules together into a bundle and use custom delimiters inside the bundle to split and separate those scripts. Unlike other mechanisms we want to ensure these existing packaging practices are supported by the WAICT solution.

**Limit the performance impact when the integrity and transparency mechanisms are enabled**
As integrity verification can be performance demanding for very large sites, we want to minimize the overhead. For example, adding signature-based mechanisms would be prohibitively expensive as every resource would need to be signed.

**Reuse existing security and privacy mechanisms as much as possible**

In order to minimize the engineering efforts and changes to the standard we propose to extend existing mechanisms in a retro-compatible manner. Typically we can leverage things like CSP and SRI and minimally extend them in order to cover the typical content of a security critical web application. These changes should be minimal and not impact the existing ecosystem.

### Infrastructure models

**The maximal security level can be provided to infrastructures that both generate and serve the content (gmail, whatsapp…) because there is no delegation of trust. However the goal of this project is to remain compatible with multiple infrastructure models**.

We believe we can provide stronger guarantees to sites for the all following cases:

- Hosting content
- Delegating hosting content
- Hosting content \+ delegating integrity guarantees
- Hosting manifest \+ delegating content
- Delegate trust entirely

###

### Proposed strategy

We propose to work through the Integrity, Consistency and Transparency problems in two steps:

- Step 1: handle Integrity of Web Applications as a standalone mechanism
- Step 2: handle Consistency and Transparency of Web Applications as a second step

**Preparing the standardization**

The idea is to create a minimal prototype at each step to ensure that the base proposal for standardization is “reasonable” and covers the main use cases of this team and then go for open discussion as soon as possible when we have reasonable alignment.

**Possible timeframe for prototyping, standardization and deployment**

It seems plausible that we can deploy experiments across browsers before the end of 2025\.
Standardization can take a longer amount of time though we think 2026 is plausible, especially for the integrity part which requires a limited amount of work at W3C.

### Starting point: the CodeVerify WebExtension/WhatsApp, Instagram and FB

**E2EE Messaging: How Meta has adapted to increased security requirements**

The fundamental principle we were chasing was bringing the guarantees mobile users have when they download an app from the Google Play Store or App Store: for the same version of an app any user will *always* get the same binary.

If we extend this concept to the web, what we need is a way to ensure users on the same release (revision) of the website will execute the same code.

The trivial approach is to bundle *all the code* for the release together, but for websites of facebook.com’s size (60 MB gzipped) this is performance prohibitive.

Instead we recognize that users will use some subset of the JS for the given revision, and we need to ensure that the subset of JS is part of the release, and the release itself is internally consistent.

We do this by generating a hash of all packages (sets of modules) that are part of the release at build time. This ensures that the modules and packages for the release haven’t been modified. Next, we hash the set of package hashes to ensure that no code is added or removed to the release itself. These hashes we refer to as the manifest. This should be sufficient to ensure the integrity of the JS that would run for any given page load.

Next we need a way to ensure at runtime the integrity of the JS that runs in the browser. We need a couple of things to do this. We insert the manifest shortly after page load, so we don’t impact the performance of the initial load. Next, we built an open-source browser extension to verify the code at runtime. It’s open source so people can see exactly what we are doing to verify the code (e.g. not just `return true`). It creates a MutationObserver that grabs all the script tags. It detects when the manifest is inserted and checks it for internal consistency (does the root hash match if we hash the set of package hashes?). Once we know the manifest is “good”, we check all the script tags by redownloading the referenced JS, splitting the result by package, hashing them, then checking that they’re present in the manifest.

A couple of other notes about checking the integrity of the page. We have to redownload the JS because there is no browser API that provides the returned JS of a `<script src=<some url>/>` tag. We ensure that these URLs have no-cache headers to prevent time of check/time of use issues. We ensure there are no dynamically executed scripts by enforcing `wasm-unsafe-eval` and no `unsafe-inline` directive. Also, we serve the manifest to *all* users and avoid logging so we have no idea *which* users have the protection installed.

The above covers one part of the problem, ensuring that the subset of JS executed in the page is part of the release. The second part is transparency, or how does the user know that the code executed isn’t a one off just for them?

We partnered with Cloudflare to host our root hashes to solve this problem. When we build the hashes at build time we send Cloudflare the root hash, domain, and release. Anyone can go fetch the list of root hashes for a given covered domain of ours. The extension, as part of the internal manifest consistency check, looks up the root hash from Cloudflare for the given release and domain (facebook/messenger/instagram/whatsapp), and ensures that it matches the computed value from the inlined manifest. Cloudflare is contractually obligated to write these root hashes only once so we can’t modify them after the fact.

The last issue to be aware of is hiding in plain sight. It’s hard to prevent all bad code from shipping, so we opt for visibility. We provide a reference to all the source code for a given release. You can download the source, and manifest, then check against the root hash from Cloudflare, it will all match.

There’s definitely a couple of things to improve on as we consider (re)building this in the browser. First, it avoids the whole class of time-of-check/time-of-use issues because you have access to the original downloaded JS source. Second, we should try to avoid the runtime third party dependencies for transparency. A thought is double signing the roothash-revision tuple. We sign the tuple, hand it off to Cloudflare (or whoever the third party transparency host is) and they sign it, and make it accessible for download, so others can verify. But\! We provide the public keys to the browser so we can decrypt with both keys and then verify the root hash. It provides similar guarantees without the runtime traffic requirement.

### Proposed initial technical solution for Integrity

#### Integrity: Content Security Policy Extension

```
Content-Security-Policy:
integrity-manifest-src 'url';
integrity-manifest-hash 'hash'; <- hex encoded hash of the manifest
integrity-enforcement-level strict;
integrity-enforcement-types script style;
integrity-enforcement-time timestamp-not-before timestamp-not-after;

Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only:
integrity-manifest-src 'url';
integrity-manifest-hash 'hash';
integrity-enforcement-types script style;

Possible additions:
	integrity-page-hash 'hash';    <- avoid the roundtrip to get the manifest
integrity-resource-origin 'self';                 <- helper for browsers?
integrity-package-separator '<some-package-delimiter>';
```

integrity-manifest-src

- **‘url’** : The url where the browser can fetch metadata about the manifest

Integrity-manifest-hash

- **‘hash’** : The hex encoded hash of the manifest

integrity-enforcement-level

- ‘**strict**’ : The resource will not be loaded/unlocked into the page until it has passed the integrity check (splash screen)
- ‘**enforce**’: The page will be loaded and notifications will be sent to the users to inform about the status of the check
- ‘**report**’ : The page will be loaded and notifications will be only sent to developers similar to report-uri

integrity-enforcement-types (types as defined by SRI)

- **‘script’**
- **‘style’**
- **‘static’** \<- New: this is for the rest of the page, hash of the static page prior to populating subresources
- **‘binary’** \<- New: wasm, images… ?

Integrity-enforcement-time

- **‘Timestamp-not-before’** : The timestamp for the beginning of the enforcement
- **‘Timestamp-not-after** : The timestamp for the end of the enforcement

integrity-page-hash

- **‘hash’** : The hash of the page
- Note that this is subtle and will likely be revisited. *The properties that you get from a website hosting themselves and a third party hosting are quite different.*

The idea here would be to avoid the roundtrip of fetching the manifest for everything that can be bundled in the page in the first load.

integrity-resource-origin (not strictly needed, help for browsers)

- ‘**self**’ :  All resources from the manifest must be loaded from the same origin as the site
- **‘remote-allowed’** : Some of the sub-resources present in the manifest can be loaded from different origins

The idea of discriminating by origin is that browsers would be able to immediately set the result of the integrity check based on origin and immediately discard the value. This should be feasible by relying on the manifest content directly but might be slower. Overall I believe that this could be treated as an optimization of the performance.

integrity-package-separator

- ‘**\<some-package-delimiter**’ :  Actual value of what the origin uses to delimit it’s packages.

Large sites package together multiple bundles of modules, the hashes of which are in the manifest separately. The browser would need to separate and trim, before hashing and verifying the sub-contents.

**Proposed default value for initial experiments**

The proposed target for experimentation is to ship the CSP at the “enforce” level for “scripts” as the baseline (which more or less gives what Meta’s Code Verify provides) and to gradually attempt to transit to more resource types and towards including “every” subresource types.

Convinced that the load of manifest metadata would work but wants us to think about performance impact.

**Proposed initial manifest and metadata format for initial experiments**

```javascript
<script type="application/json" name="integrity-page-manifest">
{
    "manifest":[
        "6f23b72be81f214cebdf3eee76af4b94320fe57e80077cbbf9a76a8280deed01",
        ...
        "a59aae2cf90e43069ec20790b7c928bff812ae7be6371fe1fe67d73a477431de"
    ],
    "manifest_metadata":{
               "integrity_hash":"e5bacf57641015ac8ced80b4d701ac8c3550d7c44b65711d18651d8873291b96",
        "version": "v1",
    },
    "transparency":{
        "signature": "<signature value>",
        "publickey": "<embedded public key>",
        "additional": [{
     "signature": "<3rd party 1 signature value>",
     "publickey": "<embedded 3rd party 1 public key>",
 },{
     "signature": "<optional 3rd party 2 signature value",
     "publickey": "<embedded 3rd party 2 public key",
 }],
    }
}
</script>...some point later, additional JS gets loaded<script type="application/json" name="integrity-page-manifest" >...</script>

```

#### More about the threat model and security properties

**Resilience against downgrade attacks**
For sites that opt-in, there is a need to have an HSTS like mechanism to prevent downgrade. The preferred solution at this point would be to extend the CSP to provide the anti-downgrade signal instead of relying on an HTTP header. Independently of the mechanism, the idea is to prevent anyone from removing the CSP opportunistically (especially when the page is served by a third party). A browser which has seen the value will display an error page in the style of HSTS errors, we probably need a very similar or identical UX.

#### Cross signing manifests for stronger authentication

**What are the high level problems here?**
1\) The developers need a third party signer for their manifest

2\) The browser needs to have a trust anchor for the object signing certificate or public key

3\) Revocation can be handled

**Code signing requires a new certificate root store in browsers**

- As it will not be allowed by the cab forum to reuse TLS certificates to sign objects, we need the CAB forum to extend rules for that usage.
- In most browsers, we should be able to extend the root store with code signing root and intermediates easily.

**Avoid changing the trust model for code signing**

- The way to handle code signing certificates can be similar to the way we handle TLS certificates both in terms of expiration, revocation and trust (eIDAS…)
- If TLS certificate keys are already delegated to a third party to authenticate the TLS channel, the simplest path forward would be to follow a similar approach with code signing: trust the delivering service to authenticate not only the TLS channel but also the delivered content by signing the integrity manifest.
- A stronger property would be to have the content owner to sign the manifest but this would entail having a separate trust chain for the content itself and to rely on a company name or some other information than the domain name itself. As we have seen with EV certification, this doesn’t really work, using this approach will be both a technical and policy challenge as well as a deployment burden that might be unrealistic to overcome.
- To enhance trust, the publisher of the content can use a  transparency log for the application should be verified by the owner of the content on submission or on a regular basis.

**Reuse existing tools to obtain object-signing certificates**

- The ideal deployment scenario doesn’t modify the current trust infrastructure and potentially reuses some of the tools used in existing deployments. For example, an extension of certbot for developers to fetch the certificate for signing could be lightweight.
- A developer getting a TLS certificate for the domain could also get a code signing certificate (potentially paired with the TLS certificate) and renew these certificates in the exact same timelines as TLS certificates.

### Proposed initial technical solution for Transparency **(Very preliminary discussions just started \- In Progress)**

#### Transparency : Browsers have very limited specification/implementation needs

**Flexibility of the transparency mechanisms**

One of the core goals of this work is to be able to combine Integrity and Transparency mechanisms in a coherent and secure way. To that effect we designed a clean boundary where the manifest can be signed by either a certificate or a transparency log and eventually cross signed. This flexibility will allow different deployments based on the expected security and privacy properties designed by the site. With modern transparency data structures we can envision that we can operate very secure and cheap logs that improve over the CT model and lean towards BT or KT but with more efficient data structure and reduced costs.

For that reason the interface between integrity and transparency can be reduced to one or more signature.

**Performance requires to avoid runtime round trips**

The mechanisms in place should not cause additional synchronous roundtrips, which means that all information needed to exercise integrity and transparency mechanisms should be contained in the initial requests to the site as much as possible. Note that some of the additional benefits from the transparency (e.g. audit) can be exercised separately from the loading and integrity check of the page.

**Preserving privacy by not introducing a third party**

As we need to provide privacy, no additional party should know anything about the website being visited compared to what is happening in the current setting. This leads us to think that we should rely on optimized versions of existing  approaches such as KeyTransparency and Certificate transparency. In particular we can use proof of inclusion of the integrity mechanisms into the transparency log instead of fetching live information from a third party. This is very much the approach already in use with certificate transparency.

**How to extend the existing integrity use case with transparency**

High level overview. The root hash and revision combo are signed and we share this signature publicly somewhere. Then we send this new signature and a link to the corresponding public key down as part of the manifest bundle. The browser will verify the hash with the public key to ensure provenance. This should cover use cases like Wikipedia that use a CDN to serve their traffic and might not want to go the extra mile. This is a slightly lower bar, but trading off for accessibility. For a use case like Meta, we would want to take an extra step and also sign the root hash before passing to a third party for secondary signing.

1) \<optional, wiki use case ignores\> Meta signs root hash \=\> part 1 signed hash
2)
   1) \<Meta\> Send part 1 signed hash to Cloudflare (or similar) which returns \=\> part 2 signed hash
   2) \<Wiki\> Third party CDN signs root hash \=\> signed hash
3) Enhance the manifest “spec” to include links to one or more signed pairs
   1) Manifest contains the following new info:
      \<....
           "transparency": {
              "signature": "",
              "publickey": "",
              "additional": \[{
                  "signature": "",
                  "publickey": "",
               },{
                  "signature": "",
                  "publickey": "",
               }\],
           }
      …/\>

Including links to the public key for verification (if the links change, the key has been rotated. Okay to cache on the browser side, then refresh on change)

The browser can then process the list of hashes. Use the public key for each to verify.

The benefit of the double signing is that clients supporting this mechanism have a cryptographic proof that the content has been signed by the content creator before being sent to the CDN; or in the case of the content creator being the same entity as the entity which serves the content, the second signature can be a public statement from a third party that some specific content was signed (this is particularly useful in the case where no transparency mechanism exists).

**Possible proposal for the double signing approach**

[Here is one proposal](https://docs.google.com/document/d/15PaxeWcRNTvjZzrwI1JpUKqooyMv6kmK12H51v9i-ig/edit?usp=sharing) by Michael Rosenberg for the double signing approach

### FAQ

**Question: can the user override the CSP setting?**

- Yes, the browser should have the ability to upgrade the level of security if supported by the site and advertised in the CSP.

**Question: why standalone manifests instead of inlining integrity values?**

- This allows to verify the authenticity of the resource hashes with a single signature
- Audit and logging is easier and doesn’t require committing the entire content and all sub resources in the absence of a transparency log.
- This is not more work than [https://github.com/whatwg/html/pull/10269](https://github.com/whatwg/html/pull/10269) SRI for import maps.

**Question: can we cover all resource types?**

- Technically we can’t because user data is needed and the generation of the manifests cannot be handled at runtime. It would also cause trouble for transparency due to the sizes and have a cluttering effect that is better to avoid.
- Streamed or large resources are difficult to handle and can benefit from a different enforcement level (see other questions below).

**Question: do we want to handle streams at all?**

- As scripts are triggering the establishment of streamed data, we could consider streams as trusted if the scripts that creates the stream has been integrity checked

**Question: do we want to treat integrity of third party iframes and recursive loads ?**

- When first loading the site, the page is checked for integrity. We propose that iFrames, because they are vetted by the creator of the page and created by the manifest should not be required to provide integrity, however we recommend that the site loaded in this iFrame should also have the integrity mechanism enabled to avoid confusing users.

**Question: do we want to make this even more flexible ?**

- eg. enforce for scripts and report for style ?
- We could define integrity-enforcement-strict ‘type’ and integrity-enforcement-type ‘type’ but this seems more difficult to understand and implement, so we would be inclined not to provide this mechanism.

**Question: why inlining a CSP into the meta and a HTTP header?**

- Because the CSP is contained in the page, it can be covered by manifest and be logged in the transparency mechanism, unlike the content of an HTTP header.
- We need to have a discussion about using a dedicated HTTP header or use CSP.

**Question: how does creating indirection for manifest fetching affect performance ?**

- This is both a performance issue and a security concern. The most generic solution seems to inline the main manifest and have a pointer to the longtail to avoid roundtrips?

**Question: what are the implications on pages that serve JS from multiple manifests ?**

- Could going with this approach make things more difficult for this use case, or do we feel it's the same regardless if it's the initial load or subsequent ones.

**Question: what are the implications here for sites that use CDNs vs serve their own ?**

- This relates to the general question of “can the service provider afford to serve the manifest themselves” ?
- We think there is a need to solve the two issues when the content provider is hosting or delegating serving the content to the users.

**Question: how do we prevent web extensions from intercepting fetches ?**

- Looks like Firefox allows web extensions to be loaded first and to intercept the content before it is rendered in the page (modulo some strict rules).
- We can move to prevent request modification. More generally the extensions should be explicitly requested to act on a protected website AFTER integrity has been checked.
- If we don’t want to prevent it then the integrity should be reported as broken.

**Question: why not relying on singing WebBundles ?**

- Many applications are too large to be signed in one go. This would be useful for only small websites (in size) which is not the only goal. Covering large websites such as Facebook.com is critical.
- We want a solution that works for the worst case scenario and also easily applies to the small website with little burden.

**Question: why not using signature based subresource-integrity tags ?**

- For performance reasons hash-based manifests SRI tags are much more efficient as the number of subresources on major sites can be very large (hundreds) and hashing is significantly faster than signature verification (not even considering PQ signatures).
- In the case where we want to sign or cross-sign a manifest instead of individual resources, we can reduce to one or two signature verifications which is significantly more efficient for sites with thousands of resources.
- Having this mechanism would only cover the case of a low number of sub resources and not the generic case which can handle both.

**Question: can we use the Origin Policy somehow?**

- Possibly, however, we do not necessarily want to require such a heavy mechanism when it is easy for the owner of the site to display the CSP once and rely on the downgrade-prevention mechanism to ensure that the CSP is enforced for a specific amount of time.

**Question: should (and if so, how should) we support multiple revisions of a website within a given “session”?**

- For facebook.com (and similar) this is supported in CodeVerify. The use case is as follows: A user loads the page, we have a limit on how long we will serve the revision that was loaded with the page, after 72 hours we will no longer serve the original revision and will now serve any new features using the most recent revision. (We also will trigger a full reload on any page transition, but sometimes users sit and chat or just scroll forever)
- If a full page reload does not occur we need to continue to verify the page, but with the new version. We embed the manifest for the new version in the page, and the extension processes that, and we tag new script tags with the version they originate from so we can verify each against the correct manifest.
- Calling this out so we can consider how to handle this use case. My suggestion would be to have a `<meta />` tag for inlining the manifest for the page load and additional tags could be added to cover subsequent revisions being boot-loaded into the page.

**Question: do the proposed mechanisms need to be coupled or can they be separated ?**
